{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"b0130889-a58f-41fd-bbaa-791eb793c968","content":"I don't see a `.dmp` file in the current directory. Could you provide the path to your crash dump file?\n\nIn the meantime, here's a quick guide on how to analyze a .NET crash dump:\n\n### Tools you can use:\n\n1. **`dotnet-dump analyze <file.dmp>`** — interactive CLI debugger (install via `dotnet tool install -g dotnet-dump`)\n2. **`lldb` with SOS plugin** — on Linux\n3. **WinDbg / Visual Studio** — on Windows\n\n### Common commands inside `dotnet-dump analyze`:\n\n| Command | Purpose |\n|---|---|\n| `clrstack` | Managed call stack of current thread |\n| `pe` (PrintException) | Show last exception details |\n| `dumpheap -stat` | Heap summary (memory issues) |\n| `threads` | List all managed threads |\n| `setthread <id>` + `clrstack` | Inspect a specific thread |\n| `dso` (DumpStackObjects) | Objects on the stack |\n\n### Typical workflow:\n```bash\ndotnet-dump analyze myapp.dmp\n# Then inside the REPL:\n> pe              # check for unhandled exception\n> threads         # find the faulting thread\n> setthread <id>\n> clrstack        # get the stack trace\n```\n\nPlease share the dump file path (or upload it), and I can walk through the analysis with you.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"b16c2f81-75eb-40a1-b59f-b6664d29dd09","outputTokens":338},"id":"319fde40-72e4-4dab-a095-8c57705f17c7","timestamp":"2026-04-08T01:08:37.420Z","parentId":"932e12f8-92af-427e-a24a-5dfb94b7de22"}
